[4.2 Views]
	- "with"
		-> allows us to assign a name to a subquery for use as often as desired, but in one particular query only.

		* we present a way to extend this concept beyond a single query by defining a "view".

	(4.2.1 View Definition)
		- "create view" command
			-> give the view a name and state the query that computes the view.
				ex)
					create view v as <query expression>;

					create view faculty as
						SELECT ID, name, dept_name
						FROM instructor;

		- the db system stores the query expression associated with the view relation.

		- whenever the view relation is accessed, its tuples are created by computing the query result.

		* differ from the "with" statement
			-> views, once created, remain available until explicitly dropped.

			-> "with" is local to the query in which it is defined.

	(4.2.2 Using Views in SQL Queries)
		- view may become out of date if the relations used to define it are modified.
			-> to avoid this, views are usually implemented as follows:
				1) when we define a view, the db system stores the definition of the view itself, rather than the result of evaluation of the query expression that defines the view.

				2) wherever a view relation appears in a query, it's replaced by the stored query expression.

				* whenever we evaluate the query, the view relation is recomputed.

	(4.2.3 Materialized Views)
		- "materialized views"
			-> if the actual relations used in the view definition change, the view is kept up-to-date.

		- "materialized view maintenance" (view maintanence)
			-> process of keeping the materialized view up-to-date

		* some may perform "lazily", some may perform "periodically"

	(4.2.4 Update of a View)
		- SQL view is "updatable" when
			1) the "From" clause has only one db relation

			2) "select" clause contains only attribute names of the relation and does not have any expressions, aggregates, or "distinct" specification.

			3) any attribute not listed in the "select" clause can be set to null; it does not have a "not null" constraint and is not part of a primary key.

			4) the query does not have a "group by" or "having" clause.
			

